  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/637cd857e4f781d6d7bbdb570fa8c227d64d4298" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -4.171ex; width:43.273ex; height:9.509ex;" alt="{\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}y(t)&amp;=\left[1+{\frac {m(t)}{A}}\right]c(t)\\&amp;=\left[1+m\cos \left(2\pi f_{m}t+\phi \right)\right]A\sin \left(2\pi f_{c}t\right)\end{aligned}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>In this simple case <i>m</i> is identical to the <a href="#Modulation_index">modulation index</a>, discussed below. With <i>m</i> = 0.5 the amplitude modulated signal <i>y</i>(<i>t</i>) thus corresponds to the top graph (labelled "50% Modulation") in figure 4.
</p><p>Using <a href="/wiki/Prosthaphaeresis#The_identities" title="Prosthaphaeresis">prosthaphaeresis identities</a>, <i>y</i>(<i>t</i>) can be shown to be the sum of three sine waves:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle y(t)=A\sin(2\pi f_{c}t)+{\frac {1}{2}}Am\left[\sin \left(2\pi \left[f_{c}+f_{m}\right]t+\phi \right)+\sin \left(2\pi \left[f_{c}-f_{m}\right]t-\phi \right)\right].\,}">
